title: 1998 YAMAHA  YZ  250 YZ250  YZ 250 DIRT BIKE PROJECT
text: WILL NOT RESPOND TO 'IS THIS BIKE STILL AVAILABLE " text messages, but yet I'm still receiving them that go unanswered, as you all know no one wants a project without knowing if it will run, and having to deal with getting the legal pink slip.  Someone should open up a dirt bike wrecking yard in their backyard like the guy in the bay area should do. I won't mention his name, but he wants to sell whole parts bikes at ridiculously high prices! I've sold him 2 parts bikes at just $100 each!  At the time, I didn't know about E B A Y, as I could of found the ancient parts needed for these bikes and could of seen if they were running bikes! Oh, them days are long gone!   I think I should hold the record for the most longest, boring Craigslist ad ever to be posted in the world !!!!  Who agrees with me ?  IF I WERE TO GET LIKE 20 PEOPLE ALL WANTING the expensive  PARTS,  all at once, THIS BUILD WOULD BE PARTED OUT!   Just added up the total spent, with the 2 parts NOT in the parts listing, total came to $4400.00 and I have it listed at just $2,000!! Crap! I could of purchased a running bike on C R A I G S L I S T at that price! Darn Madera nurse! I wish I would of have not listen to her when she told me to put my mind to work and do something I enjoy doing!!!!   Low on funds, so the reason why I cannot finish this project, buy the coolant, oil up the air filter, change the motor oil, get the gas and pre-mix oil ETC.      TEXT FIVE-HUNDRED-FIFTY NINE-SEVEN-TEN-FOUR THREE-FOUR-ZERO  if interested in purchasing my build at $2,000 FIRM.  1998 YAMAHA YZ 250 PROJECT!   E B A Y BUILD! Project has  not yet been started by me, needs fluids. All  parts have been purchased from E B A Y and ROCKY MOUNTAIN OEM/ ATV.  I have over the listed price in parts, including shipping, so FIRM on price!  Seller of the frame went and had the frame powder coated after sand blasting it, so the V I N  #  I cannot see! I looked on the internet and there it  said the V I N could be found on the frame under the engine somewhere!  I was like, "0000PS" but didn't locate it. But this was after the motor was installed into the frame.  He stated to me that  it is as clear as day to read. I have the sellers name and telephone # , just tried hunting for it, couldn't find it. Good news! I just found it! Strange how on this slip, it states 30 lbs. The motor should weigh more, Im guessing, maybe not!  So should  the frame and SUB frame he shipped to me. Frame and SUB is all metal, not aluminum!  I will probably be the one that will be writing up a Bill of Sale as you will be purchasing this bike from me, not him.  I need this project out of my bedroom ! I will show you on my old cellphone, if it can power up still and I can go back on my E B A Y 's buying  page, but probably not though as the thing broke,  and service is shut off,  so the reason why I took the photos from the old phone with this new one,  all the parts l bought and the total I put into this build to show you I am taking a huge loss on the price! I have the parts written  down and the total, so you're just going to have to believe me. I am disabled from a stroke so my mind and damaged brain is not capable of allowing me to return back to riding dirt bikes safely   anymore, something I have been doing since I was like 4 years old, maybe 5 or 6. just turned  51 on February the 5th.  Lord I'm old !  Text 23 hours a day at FIVE-HUNDRED- FIFTY -NINE-SEVEN-TEN-FOUR -3-FOUR-ZERO if interested. Clutch cable needs to be hooked up, the rear wheel when l tighten down the axle nut, makes the rear wheel not spin OK.  I might have the wheel spacers on the wrong side! I will include the bolt and nut kit I bought to install parts with, but most items on E B A Y, used parts, the seller includes them fasteners as they are parting out their bikes,  and there is really nothing else to add to this build as it is complete. A few pictures show the bike as I was building it, but it will roll under her own parts. Stupid me, what I should of done was snap a photo of the bare frame, and everytime a part was added to it,  take a picture. I  do know the motor went into the frame first, that was a job for this disabled male with a broken arm, well the arm was broken in the dirt bike crash,  during the stroke,  and still it feels as though there is a cast still on it that is squeezing the arm. Also it feels like someone is squeezing my hand right now.  I rolled up 2 towels and placed them across the lower part of the frame , to protect the finish , then placed the motor on the 2 towels, then started to get the engine bolts and top mounting bracket  installed. Dealerships  has their way on which side the bolt goes through the hole and what side they place the nut on. I didn't strip this bike down, so?? Then came the triple clamps,  the old grease was completely wiped off of the steering headset bearings, lots of fresh grease was placed on those bearing roller things, AND I even got a small flat blade screwdriver and gently turned each roller and used the flat blade and forced grease into each cavity. Almost used the whole tube at that location. Also the swingarm bearings, under neath them black dust caps, got a wipe down and grease placed under there, too. I've taken apart a 1985 XR 600 that I had that frame powder coated, and l got to restore that bike my way. Frame was powdercoated white, l found a swingarm on E B A Y that was powder coated the frame's orange color, had blue brand new PRO-LINK decals on it, I did 100% all new plastics, including a brand new tank, tank that cost me $350 from the dealership, sold that build for a cheap $500. Stupid me!"   Then, I can't remember if the forks went on next, or was it the radiators, tank, and shrouds, and I built it that way. Stupid stroke. Also, in building the sub frame, it all had to be disassembled to get all of them fasteners to bolt up. Picture shows it as 1 piece with the airbox, side panels, spark arrestor, ETC The seat was just placed on the sub frame for the photo, installing the sub frame  was a job for this disabled male here with his damaged brain and a non usable arm and hand. . After the motor was mated to the frame, I lifted the frame with motor attached, boy was it already heavy, onto the blue plastic city's recycling bin you see in a few photos. After awhile, that blue bin started to slowly give way,  so I had to get the metal stand, yep, also from E B A Y. What was funny when that stand arrived, I simply just pulled it out of its shipping box, and it was ready for usage. As with me kidding around, I emailed the place that sold the stand to me, saying, " I'm not particularly fond of my purchased item from you not having to be assembled when I removed  it from its box" as a joke I sent that message! They gave me like a $8 refund! I was joking with them ! Still, some people like to make their customers  happy! Will I be including the stand upon someone buying this dirt bike from me? Probably not as I have other bikes here at the house that this stand could be used for.  And since this stand can slide easily on carpet, the next bike build will need to be placed on it, whenever that day comes.  Also with the loss I am already taking, no need to be adding  to it.  Will let it go for an additional $60.   Anyways:  The seller of the motor and frame included the foot pegs, just was being a jerk and only sent me 1 foot peg spring,  but I think he went and sabotaged the pegs,  as on the part that your boot touches, them spikes,, all of them spikes around the edge of the pegs,, looks  as though they were all filed down recently, making the tips sharp, so do NOT wear good expensive boots while riding with these foot pegs. Nice aftermarkets can be found on E B A Y, stocks also. Seller was an a$$ hole to me during the bidding process as I asked him to send a Bill of Sale  with the frame,  and any hole on the frame, to insert the correct fastener in it, so that I know something needs to be bolted in that hole. Like where the coil bolts onto, he could of put back the correct bolts in those holes as he included the coil. Also, the top end job  he stated was done, he could of included a receipt.  Dont ask me what all was done as he didn't send any paperwork with this motor. A compression check will need to be done. if this motor is even good, I am taking a huge gamble  on this mystery motor. Still these parts aren't like toilet paper, an item that females use everyday,  and us males, every third day so parting her /  him out would  be a slow process.  Help out a poor disabled  man and take on this  year's summer project, bike is a project. Looks like a dirt bike! The suspension has not yet been tested, so hopefully the fork seals are great and the rear shock isn't blown. Forks were only purchased at a price of just $60, then the $40 for shipping, the sales tax brought it up to the price listed in the parts list. Forks cost me less than the rear shock ????????????????? But then I had to purchase a set of triples!   THANK YOU FOR reading this far!  UPDATE:  I switched the wheel spacers around, rear wheel spins better now! Maybe install a new chain and see what that does?  Wheel bearings? Clutch cable attached! Routed correctly? Questionable! I still need to tighten down the front sprocket, the shift pedal, as well as the kickstarter, as we all like those certain items at a specific spot on them shafts, to get your boot under the shifter, where to correctly place the starter on the shaft,   install the fluids, get some gas and change the blood, ( motor oil)  and keep my fingers crossed the bike fires up! I know the clutch and throttle cables will probably need to be adjusted better, but I'm only a novice in doing stuff like that, l know front brakes work great, and the rear has a low brake pedal, will work,  but you got to really push the pedal to the carpet! Bike has NOT left the bedroom since it was put together, so the tires has only touched the bedroom carpet! OOOOOPS, bike is on its E B A Y bought stand, and the front tire is on a piece of cardboard.  Maybe I'm just a damaged weakling? The brake reservoir is full, I'm an old school guy, all my dirt bikes were rear drum brakes so maybe  this is acceptable? I don't know. I do know on my rear drum brake bikes, my boot would rest on the foot peg, as well as the rear brake pedal, causing it to activate when riding, so what I would do is, back off a little on the rear brake adjustment. Saved on rear brake shoes this way. So maybe the really far down to push the rear brakes to the dirt, is this way of not riding  the rear brakes?? Rear brake assemblies can be found on E B A Y should you need to replace the set up.  Reason for the front fender being black is, with the black powder coated swingarm,  I wanted to go with a blue, black and white appearance as much as possible, so the blue and black seat.  We all know what happens to blue plastics after a crash! Yep! Those white stress marks show up. The rear fender has a white stress dot on it. My father's K L X 1 4 0, yes he is that short of a guy,, had a white rear fender, as well as a green front fender. I know Honda on a XR 600, like the 1988 year,  used a red rear fender and a white front fender. Or vise versa. Also with this bike being assembled in pieces, the blue gas tank doesn't match the blue radiator shrouds, as these parts was purchased from different sellers off of different bikes! Hence, the reason for no tank decals on the tank. I thought about purchasing a black fuel tank, but we all know how hard it is to see the fuel level with black fuel tanks!  Trust me on that. Also black parts are hard to see, so the reason I went with the white radiator guards and the white radiator hoses. You can see them better.  Now I see a white air box on E B A Y. NOPE, too expensive and I am low on funds. I won't be switching out no more parts! This is my build, I built it up my way.   LOL  The rear fender, the radiator shrouds, and the brand new front disc brake guard all share  the same shade of blue. Tank doesn't match these parts! Let's keep that a secret between buyer and builder.   Carb is supposed to be brand spanking new, a E B A Y purchased part, so hopefully no adjustment  there is needed as at the carb, things will need to be removed in order to gain access there! Just hopefully the electrical is OK and the bike fires up one day ! I placed an ad on C R A I G S awhile ago asking if the powder coating under neath where the coil bolts to, do I have to go back and scrape off the paint,, for a better ground,, and so I outlined the coil  and slowly had to scrape away the nice paint job! You will never see it. Seller of the motor and  frame is the same guy. He included the wiring harness, the CDI, the coil, and even had a clean spark plug in the head that looked brand spanking new.  Stupid me forgot to check the # on the spark plug to see if it is correct for this motor, so that is something  you will want to do before actually starting her up, and also, to check the gap. Don't want the top of the piston hitting a too long of a spark plug now!  0UCH! I ran the shifter through the gears and they are  engaging, will operate the kickstarter someday.  Thank you for reading this far, hope I haven't bored you too bad ! But please continue to be bored.   L0L Just please don't send me a bill for wasting your time.  Again, for those that cannot read, I'M NOT TAKING ANYMORE OF A LOSS ON THE PRICE AS I AM DOING AT $2000 ! $1995 WON'T buy the bike! $1999 WON'T even! I was offered $1200 by a person by text message that didn't read the whole ad,  came back with a $1300 for his final offer by text. Yes, any amount over the listed price will be greatly appreciated.  LOL I know if I had this build running and registered, it would probably sell quicker, as it will be an all year long green sticker bike. Buy this bike and part him / her out on E B A Y and make yourself a few bucks! I won't mind.   To help you guys out, prices are what I paid on E B A Y, including shipping, if the seller charged for shipping. Some items were the buy it now feature with free  shipping,  and some were the make offer, but now E B A Y is charging sales tax on auctions, just another way us citizens are getting ripped off in this world. If I remember correctly, I do believe the engine and the motor was the only 2  E B A Y listing that were actual auctions, the others were all buy it nows, and make offers. I'm pretty sure I made offers on all make offer auctions. Some items, I paid too much for. On the frame,, I got it at the starting bid,, as no one else in the world needed a 1998 YZ 250 bare frame last year. The motor, I'm guessing the seller had his  buddies bid up the auction, and when it got around to  what he wanted for it, they all stopped bidding. I think I got it for around $950 then the tax and shipping charges!   Here goes.   PARTS LIST :  MOTOR $$1149.65 FORKS $104.85 REAR SHOCK $81.19 AIR BOX $16.24 CARBURETOR $54.30 new THROTTLE $24.84.   new FRONT FENDER $30.30 REAR FENDER $50.86 SEAT $89.94 R BRAKE LINE HOSE CLAMPS $13.15 those white plastic C ' s holding  rear brake line onto swingarm FRAME and  SUB FRAME     $343.49 TRIPLE CLAMPS $106.59 FORK GUARDS 45.30 RADIATOR HOSES $ 23.80  RADIATOR SHROUDS 54.10 RADIATORS $67.10 3  # PLATES $30.00    # 61 RADIATOR LOUVERS $37.89 FRONT SPROCKET ASSEMBLY $ 18.09 REAR AXLE ASSEMBLY $45.22 FRONT CHAIN GUARD $ 17.94 FUEL / GAS TANK $317.21 FMF HEADER PIPE 301.04  MISC FRAME RUBBER $15.01 what's under the fuel tank FOOT PEG SPRINGS $10.77 AIR BOX MUD FLAP $13.80  THE 3 SPRINGS for  HEADER PIPE $12.99 CHAIN ( MISC ) $39.13 SPARK ARRESTOR $92.00 C D I RUBBER BOOT $ 20.36 MUFFLER BRACKET TOP $ 38.92 Brand new  MUFFLER BRACKET BOTTOM $32.42 Brand new  BRAND NEW GRIPS $7.97 HANDLEBARS $81.18 SHIFT PEDAL $ 19.87 BRAND NEW AIR FILTER $28.15 INTAKE CLAMP $22.90 REAR CHAIN GUARD $41.37 SWING ARM LINKAGE $37.88 FRONT BRAKE DISC GUARD $ 30.78 the new blue piece  SWING ARM $ 144.06 SWING ARM DECALS $17.52 HANDLE BAR PAD $10.83 AIR FILTER HOLD DOWN BOLT $ 8.41  WHEEL SET $423.96 CLUTCH CABLE and  LEVER WITH PERCH $ 29.55 FRONT BRAKE ASSEMBLY $81.19 REAR BRAKE ASSEMBLY $64.84 TRIPLE CLAMPS FRONT BRAKE HOLD DOWN METAL BRACKET $19.12  PLUS 3 ORDERS PLACED AT ROCKY MOUNTAIN  OEM / ATV for bolts, nuts ETC totalling almost $400. I know the rear shock was just $75 with free shipping, the tax brought the price up to the listed amount. I can't believe I paid more for the fuel tank, than I did for the FMF header pipe!   And any remaining parts I forgot,  like the brand new kill  switch, and the fuel tank's breather tube,  I'm not going to post , so firm on price at $2,000. The reason for the #61, those were purchased on E B A Y and that was the number. You may change it to whatever # you prefer. I'm just glad it wasn't # 69 ! Would of made me look like I was the pervert!  L0L In 10 more years , 61 will be my age!   Grips and the air filter are probably the only items that are brand new! 000PS, the seller of the header pipe states the pipe was NEVER used, OH and the carb is supposed to be new, the air box mounted mud flap / guard is brand new, and the throttle plastic and housing are new E B A Y items! Would like for this project to go to someone that will finally get her  to the trail someday! I will use the funds from this sale and start up another project, or maybe not! Need to support my Starbucks addiction! With me not selling this build, maybe I will get the radiator coolant, the gas and oil mixture, oil up the air filter, get her fresh oil and see if my build is a YAAAAA ! or a NAAAAA!  How my dirt bike building hobby began was, a long time ago, on E B A Y there was a 1984 YZ 80 being parted out. I wanted to turn the fuel tank into a unique piggy bank. Cut slots in the top to accept the coins.  You just simply turn the thing upside down after unscrewing the fuel tank cap to get the coins to dump out. Well anyways, the fuel tank was all complete, nice, petcock, mounting brackets, nice stock fuel tank decals ETC,  and sold for a great price! The tank arrived, a light bulb went off in my head, saying to me, I cannot afford to buy a dirtbike outright, why not build it piece by piece? And so the dirt bike building  days began. I felt sorry for the 1 guy selling the 85 YZ 80  frame on E B A Y as it only sold for $10 with free shipping. I built the bike,  a red 85 frame, 84 yellow plastics, a black seat, and a front disc brake set up, where as a stock 85 is supposed to be drums in the front. I bought a 1984 YZ80 from a  high school classmate of mine for just $300. My parents bought me a brand spanking new 1985 YZ80 that was only $1200 off the showroom floor,  or out the door,, and even included a spark arrestor!! Oh the cheap prices way back then ! With the extra parts I was getting with building the 1985, I constructed a YZ 80 with a white frame, so let's call him a 1990. The 85 I was able to get running, the 1990, I wasn't so lucky. And stupid me never attempted to diagnose why that 1 wouldnt start, I started parted it out on C R A I G S L I S T, and got the motor sold on E B A Y as a non running motor! Then came K B F L A T F A C E from E B A Y. I guess it is a parting out place on the east coast. There I bought a 1986 Honda Z50R-D frame, forks, swingarm, exhaust pipe, and handlebars from him. The fenders, seat, rear shocks, and fuel tank were all brand new reproduction parts, the motor and wheels were from a Honda Z50R, just not correct for 1986  as they were supposed to be chrome parts.  I never attempted or tried to get the Honda running, added up what I put  into the build, total came to like $1500. I placed the ad on C R A I G S L I S T, got the bike sold to a gentleman living in Pleasanton! The 1985 that I built, later I saw it reposted on CL, the seat cover was all torn up, ripped, and thrashed, I paid like $25 for the seat on E B A Y. So I can honestly say I built 4 bikes all from E B A Y auctions. Just 3 are, or should be still built.  Hopefully 1 day this YZ 250 sells.  The End, hopefully !  Reason why this ad doesn't make since is, I would go back and add to it, because of the stroke I suffered, I dont remember things right away, and so the reason for the carb being listed as brand new a few times. In staring at the fuel tanks cap new breather tube that just arrived yesterday, Valentine's Day, the hose looks as though it is too long and should be shortened by an inch. Will let the new owner decide on that. It's 3" from top of fuel cap to bottom of the nice color cap breather part on top of the hose.  OK, the end! Definitely!!

title: 2014 L BMC Trailfox carbon w/ upgrades & extras
text: This bike was way ahead of its time as one of the early long travel slacked out 29" enduro bikes. 150mm rear travel, 160 front, 1x11. It's been well cared for and is a blast to ride. It comes with many recent upgrades and a bunch of extras. Components are a mix including XTR, XX1, and a carbon wheel. I have a tendency to stockpile spare parts so that I can swap them in when it's time instead of waiting, so you won't have to spend money on this bike for quite some time. Carbon all across the front end.  The fork has some damage to one stanchion. I'll get a photo posted soon. I've polished the dings which makes them look worse, but perform better. The scratches happened almost three years ago and when seals have been replaced, there is no visible damage to the seals or fluid loss from that side. They were really upsetting when it happened, but those scratches have been completely forgotten by now.  The most recent services were Spring and Fall of 2021:  Spring 2021 - Full overhaul of fork, damper inspection, airspring o-rings and wiper seals replaced. Air cartridge and wiper seals replaced in the seatpost w/ new cable and housing. SRAM DUB bottom bracket and cranks installed w/ new chainring and chain. XX1 shifter installed. New Blunt 35 rim laced to existing Tune rear hub. New rear cassette.  Fall 2021 - Lower leg service on fork. New X01 derailleur and new derailleur hanger. New headset.  Carbon front triangle, aluminum rear Carbon handlebars RockShox Pike 160 fork, solo air CB Highline 160mm dropper post w/ CB remote Shimano SLX brakes, XTR lever for the rear. 180mm rotors SRAM Dub bottom bracket, replaced Spring 2021. SRAM direct-mount cranks. 30t OneUp chainring. X01 derailleur. XX1 shifter Kong tune hubs with Enve M60 Forty front rim and Velocity Blunt 35 rear Brand new Maxxis Aggressor 2.5 front, lightly used Aggressor 2.5 on the rear.  Extras: 2 pair brake pads, nearly new cassette, extra CB dropper wiper, Banjo Bros frame bag. I have a full set of new pivot bearing for the whole rear linkage that I just haven't installed yet. I can install them, or provide them for you to take care of in another year.  I'm out here visiting right now with the bike, but many of the extras are back in my garage.  If you buy the bike, I'll ship out a box when I get home in two weeks.  In addition to what's listed, I have extra wheels that I can add in so you have a backup or can have two types of tires ready to go and swap them according to trail conditions.   Extra wheelset: American Classic 23mm rim depth wheels Additional front wheel - Hope hub with Stan's rim all wheels are taped and sealed with valve stems.

text: These jags are fun to drive, and have AWD, and are perfect for snow.   The 2008 Jaguar X-type runs like a top. The Power steering hose popped, and I just took it off and ordered a new one. New A/C, flushed the system accumulator, pump, orifice, condenser. New emission systems, and new complete radiator, all hoses, and pipes and o rings. New water pump.  I have to smog it, or you can for the discount. $3000.00 if you smog it, $4000 if I do. 176k miles  The 2002 X-type needs a fuel pump or fuse, or relay or module. I haven't had time to do a diagnostic test to see which it is. Worse case scenario, drop the tank and put a fuel pump in for a few hundred bucks.  I just did the front end, cv axels, struts, ball joints and arms, A/C with pump, dryer, orifice, flushed the system.  $2500.00 on non op, runs with starter fluid. Bring a can and it runs like a top.  2004 Ranger FX4 video of truck here   https://youtu.be/z9JzoeA1XQg   Rebuilt Transmission and Transfer case, and I put a new slave cylinder/throwout bearing, master cylinder, clutch and flywheel, and the transmission is great now. I have a new radiator, and water pump I put in that a while back. I did the front bearings, and everything else is running great.  It has 275k miles, but keeps on ticking. So, that motor is good. I just put new plugs and wires on it. It's the heavy duty FX4 model 4x4, and really is a work horse. It has a lumber rack, about 1500 con truck from auburn as they are the best! $4500  The Harley Davidson Road King is a 2005 with 30k miles. It runs great with no issues at all. I've changed the oil bi-annually, and the transmission fluid frequently.   The neat thing about this Harley is that I bought a paint kit OEM factor identical to when I bought it. It is smokey gold, and so is the brand new paint kit, which consists of fuel tank, side panels, bags (hard), and front and back fender. I haven't put them on yet, but I can. I thought I'd get a few more scratches and dents and switch them out when I bore out the motor bigger. It will be IN SHOW ROOM CONDITION FOR A 15 year old bike. It has a tour box removable, and that did not come with the OEM new stuff I have. I want 10 grand for the bike with the $2000 paint kit tossed in, so you get a new looking bike when your ready to put some more thunder in it.     I'll get some pics up soon. Evo is a Euro brand thus the much lower level of graphics and such.  We like them as a lot of kid's bikes like these come with suspension forks which are generally not of high quality, not needed and weigh a lot more. In this configuration, you can ride some dirt, then later, if you are mostly road riding, change to a narrower slink tire.  24" in mint (as seen) or black 20" in red  Nice price for quality 7 speed bikes 24" - $349 - 7 Speed  20" - $299 - Single speed  +++++++++++++++++++++++++  New Cleary Bikes - Many colors, spec and sizes  We have 20 Cleary bikes in stock. At this time we only have new Clearys in sizes from 16" -  26". We believe that the Cleary is the best all around kids bike. The internal 3 and 5 speed hubs are so superior for kids than a derailleur that always get knock out of adjustment. The standard threadless stem set-up like on nice adult bikes means you can replace with longer stem as child ages and get another year or two out of the bike before outgrowing.   You can see the bikes here - https://cocosvariety.com/collections/kids-bikes   +++++++++++++++++++++++++  Used Diamondback 20" Mountain Bike - Orange   20" bike, 1 x 6 gripshift, suspension fork, v-brake.  This is a little lower end than we usually sell - more of a Dick's Sporting Goods brand as opposed to a true bike store brand like Giant or Specialized. The bike is of fine quality but it is very heavy.   20" wheel  Typically 6-9 years old, depending on the child. $100  +++++++++++++++++++++++++  Used Linus 16" Roadster Blue with training wheels  Some scuffs and scraps but overall this bike is in nice condition. Less than half the price of new Linus 16"s which have reached an astonishing $369 for new ones.  16" wheel Fits most riders ages 4 to 6 $160  +++++++++++++++++++++++++  Used Linus Lil Roadster in terrific condition. Blue with no training wheels  The most minor flaws distinguish it from a brand new bicycles.   20" Wheel Typically 6-9 years old, depending on the child. $275   +++++++++++++++++++++++++  Giant Animator 16" - Blue and White with training wheels  Clean condition! Was kept inside and it shows. Near new.  Small 16" wheel Generally ages 4-6 $175  +++++++++++++++++++++++++  Used Fuji 20" Performance Bike - Orange and White  Rare bike! It is a hard to find a kid's bike with the  features of an adult performance hybrid like narrow double wall rims, presta valves, threadless headset, dual pivot brakes, et al.  Ages 7 - 9 $250  +++++++++++++++++++++++++  +++++++++++++++++++++++++   After 14 years of Coco's being open 7 days a week, we have ceased having regular business hours and now people need to call to visit. We are still here 11-6 daily, closed Sundays, so just give us a call to come by and check out the scene.  Coco's buys, sells and trades new and used, vintage and modern bicycles.  Additionally, we are interested in fine art, pottery, early California, vintage automobiles, antiques, old electronics like ancient Apple Computers and vintage hi-if, 4 wheel drive adventure gear, books, records, CDs, tapes, watches and tools so we are always open to interesting trades. Our robust want list resides here - https://cocosvariety.com/pages/want-list  If you are interested in what Coco's Variety is up to, we have two newsletters.  Bike Alert! Newsletter - every bike we get, all fresh inventory, used and new, goes to the Bike Alert! first. Dispatch from the Edge's of the Coco's Variety Universe - more broad, some bikes, some cars, some garage sale reports  Subscribe to either or both here - https://cocosvariety.com/pages/newsletter-sign-up  This is not all the bikes we have. Check the website for more offerings. Cocosvariety.com  Our prices are firm and unfortunately we do need to charge sales tax. Trade-ins welcome. Credit cards ok. Would it be possible to trade a painting or a record collection for a bike? Possible!

title: 2015 Sportster Iron - Only 2958 Miles
text: I have at my shop a Super Nice - Clean 2015 Sportster Iron. The bike has a Stage 1 Performance Package which includes A Screaming Eagle Heavy Breather Intake - Vance and Hines Short Shot Exhaust - and a Dealer Tune. title: Trek Y33 Full Suspension Mountain Bike
text: When Trek introduced this light weight full suspension Y bike, it created an immediate buzz. Every bike magazine at the newsstand featured a review. In bike shops around the country there was a lot of gawking and countless test rides. My personal Trek utilizes a Y33 OCLV carbon fiber frame producing a radical looking and light weight structure that is coupled to a highly polished aluminum unified rear triangle. No pedal-induced bobbing with this design which offers predictable behavior, quick responsive steering and a pretty light carbon bike to boot!. It features Shimano Deore XT and  LX components as shown in photos, an extended reach Profile handlebar and a Cloud Nine fully adjustable rear shock  Today, this one owner, always stored inside, seldom used bike is one of the most collectable and highly desired bikes produced. I bought it new here in Florida and is offered in in mint condition with no scratches or flaws anywhere. The original leather seat is perfect. The basic original Trek All Terrain manual is also included.

title: The new bicycle
text: Help your child learn to ride with the 16" Schwinn Piston kids sidewalk bike! This rad little ride has a sweet "big kid" look, thanks to the laser-printed seat, gnarly p-wrap chain guard and a fun handlebar number plate. Since fit is key, the Piston features all new Schwinn SmartStart geometry, a complete redesign of bike geometry that matches a kid's body type to create a more comfortable, ideal riding position. This includes a lighter bike frame for added control, smaller grip handles to match smaller hands, and a more narrow pedal position to match narrow kid hips! Other kids bikes are just shrunken down versions of adult bikes, so typically the grips are too large, the pedals too wide, and the seats are too big. Thanks to the tool-free adjustable seat post, your child won't need a new bike after their next growth spurt.

title: OMNI "LA.BIKE" - Vintage "Mixte"
text: This vintage 12 speed OMNI - LA.BIKE is from an era of quality hand-built lugged frame bikes of the 1970s and 80s. The frame design called a Mixte, from the French word meaning "mixed" or "unisex". Was popular with quality European bicycle manufacturers; Peugeot, Gitane, Raleigh, Bianchi, and others. This classic design has made a comeback and is the new trend in stylish city bikes. It‚Äôs also popular with niche bicycle manufacturers and collectors.   This particular Mixte is rare because it was made in Japan by OMNI Bicycle Company.  Have you ever seen another OMNI bicycle from Japan? Japan was home of quality bicycle manufacturing in the 70s and 80s when Japan manufacturers Panasonic and Myiata hand-built lightweight, triple butted, lugged, Chromoly steel frames. Many were re-badged by other Japan manufacturers. I suspect that is the case with the OMNI Bicycle Company and this rare "LA.BIKE".    Buy this bicycle or different bike, but the idea is to get outside and ride for FUN and your good health. title: Ladies Schwinn Hybrid full refurb Fits 5ft5 to 6ft
text: 2015 Schwinn Clear Creek hybrid road bike in very pretty condition.  The bike was completely disassembled, deep cleaned, and rebuilt, piece by piece. It has new stainless steel cables, new cable housings, and new internal ball bearings. Everything works perfectly. And it rides nice and smooth.... Better than new, as mass assembled bikes don't get a mechanic's touch during build-out, often needing grease around the bearings and adjustments to most components. This one also had cheap galvanized cables on it that would rust. Those have all been replaced.  The bike has a 15 inch frame measured from the bottom bracket to the top of the seat tube. I would call this a medium size bike. A rider around 5ft5 to around 6'0 should fit fine.  The bike was completely disassembled. All the components and the drivetrain were removed, deep-cleaned, and adjusted. The front shock was removed and the headset bearings were replaced, greased, and the headset was adjusted. The wheelhub bearings were all replaced, greased, and adjusted. The internal cups and cones where all these bearings travel were all deep-cleaned to provide the cleanest and smoothest surface possible. The wheelhubs are now buttery smooth. The bottom bracket was rebuilt with new ball bearings and fresh grease, and tightened correctly. The wheels were trued, the rims and spokes were individually cleaned. The frame was cleaned and polished. The brake calipers and levers, shifters, derailleurs, cranks and chainrings, and drivetrain were all disassembled and rebuilt. There's not a nut or bolt on the bike I haven't touched.  This is a 21-speed comfort road bike with a step thru frame. The bike has street tires(700c). It has a front shock. The bike has Shimano Tourney derailleurs. It has a Shimano grip shifters. The bike has a shock absorbing seat post and matching seat and grips. The wheels have lightweight alloy rims and hubs, and have nice tires with excellent tread. The bike also has an alloy stem, alloy handlebar, and alloy seatpost to keep things light-ish. The frame is very pretty and is in like new condition.  Due to the vast amount of spam, please put the word DOG into your email and I will reply.   Use the "more ads by this user" link to see my other bikes. Link is located on the right side of the ad.    Old grease, combined with dirt, will harden and damage the operation of the bearings. This will cause internal damage, and can make your bike dangerous(especially with the headset bearings which allow you to steer). If you're looking to buy any used bike, find out when the last time the bearings were overhauled (not just a "tune-up"). If it has not been done in 5 yrs, I strongly recommend having it done.

FIY:  PTC batteries  PTC thermistor is a small disc that is found at the top of the battery.    When the temperature rises, the resistance increases.   If there is a surge current and the battery heats up significantly, the PTC will increase its resistance to limit the current.   And then the temperature will drop normal, which prevents your battery from becoming burned out.

title: EcoCross Hybrid Bamboo Bike Frameset
text: This is a brand new bike frame and fork in the manufacturer's original box. The outside of the box is cosmetically damaged but inside the frame and fork are untouched and the frame is warrantied for life.  I have one of each size. See more details and specs at https://www.greenstarbikes.com/store/frame-ecocross-hybrid  The Greenstar Bikes EcoCross Hybrid Bamboo Frame is a multi-purpose frame that can be used for any number of bike builds: mountain bike, hybrid bike, comfort bike, even a road bike. Perfect for streets, trails and off-roading, the EcoCross bamboo frame will help you zip up hills and enjoy your ride on almost any terrain. The bamboo and recycled 6061 aluminum lugged frame delivers an ultra smooth ride by absorbing micro vibrations. This affordable frame weighs only about 5 pounds, and still has all the beauty, quality, and performance of a bamboo bicycle from Greenstar Bikes. Stunningly available in black.

title: Civia Kingfield (58cm)
text: Civia Kingfield with belt drive and Nexus 8 internally geared hub, in great condition.  I've converted the drop bars to a flat bar, and upgraded the bar end shifter to a trigger shifter.  I'm pretty sure it's a 58cm, ideal for 5'9"-6'3".    I purchased this bike a decade ago (because I live in Kingfield), and have put very few miles on it, mostly because it's in such good condition, and I don't want to damage it.  This bike is super smooth, clean (no chain grease), shifts beautifully, and very comfortable to ride.    I'd love to hang on to this bike, but running out of space.   https://civiacycles.com/bikes/archive/kingfield

title: 1984 ROMIC 12 speed custom hand built road bike 59cm Reynolds 531
text: 59cm or 23‚Äù frame with 33‚Äù standover   ROMAN (Ray) J GASIOROWSKI worked at Schwinn and was involved in production of The Paramount.  After leaving Schwinn and heading up AMF, he ventured out to make his own custom built bikes in Houston.  The higher end ones like this one are basically a Schwinn Paramount built by Ray.  Full Shimano 600 group.  He died in 1996.

title: TREK Navigator 300 Comfort Bike
text: A large TREK Navigator 300. 21.5 inches, 32 inch standover height for the taller rider (maybe 5'10-6'3). title: I buy: fridge, washer, beds, pool tables,  furniture, spas, clubs
text: I buy new / used: appliances, refrigerators, washer dryer,  mattress, pool tables, jacuzzi,  steam carpet cleaners. pressure washing  units, cars. trucks,  electric bikes,   I need your (working) full size or mini fridge. Moving? Upgraded? If you have LARGE items: appliances; refrigerator, washer, dryer, pool table, hot tub, sauna, large furniture items, recliner, sofa, cars, bikes, patio furniture, BBQ grill, meat smoker, golf clubs, etc. You deliver = we pay extra. We will pick it up and haul it away to donate for local charities supporting veterans and homeless kids or we buy it to place in rental houses. If it is in GOOD, (clean) working condition, I may want to buy it from you for cash today! For example: your fridge or mattress or appliance or bedroom set is less than 7 years old, and not something you would just throw out to the trash for bulk pickup, or if you are upgrading appliances / furniture and your old unit has a working, functional ice maker, it tests "good" as for freon and condensers and fans etc., it's not filthy with frost in the freezer or grime and slime in the refrigerator drawers... I can offer you cash if it's suitable for use or refurbishing.  Send photos of your items to this number. I buy Valley Pool tables and Diamond pool tables. a pool table is worth more if it has NEW (quality) cloth in a nice color, that won't need to be removed to move it, that has good condition rails (the cushions on pool tables last only a few years in the desert) dead-rails need replacement and that costs about $200. New felt (cloth) costs about $300 plus the cost to professionally move it, take it apart, install new cloth, rails, clean the slate, level it and repair any mechanical issues or pockets etc. so the used pool table market does not hold much value when a person can get a new custom table for only a few hundred more than your old junk pool table. Also, most "bar" tables are 7' foot or regulation is 9' foot and most 'house' tables are 8' foot, which is not standard to practice on for league players or pros. Most homes can only fit a 7 foot table with enough space around them. Hot tubs: most have a bad heater or bad pump or other issue and it's not worth moving. So, we can determine if your item is worth picking up for free, or if we need to charge you for our service. I have a helper to move big items, plus gas is very expensive and my truck needs maintenance and Ihaveto pay a helper, so I don't BUY your junk but most often, we can haul it away. For fast service, take photos inside and out from as many angles of your refrigerator and clean out your fridge first! Keep it running (plugged in) even if you had to move it to the garage. If it's stored outside, we probably won't want it because it tends to get mice, rats, and debris inside and it will usually be ruined, so even if you just got a new fridge and don't want to pay the delivery guy to haul away yours, just move it to the garage, call or text us, send a description: (measure it, width, heighth, depth from the wall) and describe it. Take a pic of the model and serial number inside where it shows the brand name and date it was built. text the pics to us. Schedule a pick up. It will be gone in 24 hours! I can even save you the delivery fee on your new stuff and bring that for you if you save your good working condition stuff for us. If we won't or can't move it, we will tell you why. If it's filthy, or has food or spilled liquids inside of the fridge, clean it, defrost it by pouring hot water in and soak up the drainage with towels. I will test it, check the temperature and thermostat and test the ice maker. Whatever you do keep it plugged in and don't lay it down on its back or side because it will ruin it in some cases and often we have to stand it up for at least as long as it was laying down so if you had it laying on its back for 24 hours I can't even test it for 24 hours. If it's working, you can send video or pics. Call today for free estimate! No Habla Espanol

title: DiamondBack Kalamar LX Upright Comfort Bike w. 28" Tires & 1 X 7 Drive
text: This is one of those restorations where you reach the point that you ask yourself, "If I spend any more making it perfect in every way, will I be able to get my money back selling it?"  For me, the answer is "no," and that works out pretty well for you.  The DiamondBack Kalamar LX sold for about $200 brand new, which makes it a decent-but-lower-line model in DiamondBack's catalog.  It's a perfect bike for someone looking to tool around the neighborhood, ride some local bike trails, commute to the train station, or use as a "Fire Island" bike.  Here's what you may or may not want to change about this bike:  1.  It has some rust on the cassette (the chainrings in the rear) although the gears switch as well as I'm sure they ever did.  Keep it greased and you can get many miles out of it, as-is.  A replacement would be about $25 + labor at your local shop.  There is also some rust on minor parts, but it is mostly aesthetic in nature and should not affect the performance of the bike. 2.  The original chain was completely rusted out so I had to replace it with a slightly-used chain, which had to be connected via the old-school method of popping the pin in and out.  I've had chains last for hundreds of miles that way, but you might want to replace it for $10 with your own labor. 3.  The saddle has a few nicks on it that may or may not bother you.  Most people like to choose their own saddle, anyway, so you might even have one on your current bike to transfer over.  Schwinn sells a big, fat, cushy saddle for $25. 4.  I replaced the inner tube of the front tire with a brand new one; however, I only had one with a Presta-style valve, which is different than the one on the other wheel, which has a Schraeder-style (old standard) valve.  When pumping the tires, you'll need a pump that can handle both, which many current pumps do.  Usually, you have to unscrew the pump head and turn one piece around.  Otherwise, for less than $10, you can purchase a new tube that matches.  They also make adapters for a couple of dollars, but that's jumping the gun a little.  You can see that replacing all these parts before offering the bike for sale would have cost me an additional $70 or more, which means I could not sell the whole bike for $50.  If YOU would like to invest in these parts, you can still have a nice bike for about $125-150.    Unless you're looking to make this your bike-to-end-all-bikes, I don't think you need to spend anything at all on it.  Now, here's what's really cool about this bike:  1.  It's in pretty nice shape, with the exception of a few scratches. 2.  It's a 17" frame (good for someone around 6' tall) and it's got 28" (700 X 40c) Kenda tires (nice, large diameter for better speed with fewer revolutions of the pedals) that appear to have very low mileage on them. 3.  It's got a simple 1 X 7 (one gear in front, seven in the rear) drive system with gripshifters for easy clicking from gear to gear.  There is no derailleur on the front, which makes maintenance and shifting a lot easier. 4.  I have installed a new shifter cable and a new rear brake cable. 5.  The bike is designed with upright handlebars for an easy-on-the-back experience and better visibility for you when on the road. 6.  The Kalamar LX has connectors (braze-ons) for a rear rack that you can add on yourself, making it a great bike for commuting or riding to the beach. 7. The bike comes with a water bottle cage and front/rear reflectors to comply with local codes. 8.  It's fifty bucks.  If you are handy with bicycles, this is sort of a no-brainer, as I'm sure you can save a lot of money swapping parts off other bikes and/or handling installation of any new parts by yourself.  If you are not, the beauty of this bike is that, even after paying a local bike mechanic to perform all the optional upgrades and add-ons suggested above, it falls within the price range of the less expensive department store bikes that are hard to come by right now.  Please contact me if you have any questions or would like to come by and see the bike in person.  Thank you!

title: Bianchi Pista
text: For sale is my lightly modified 53 cm chrome Bianchi pista with $450 in modifications (https://www.bianchiusa.com/bikes/track/pista/). The rear hub is a flip-flop, however, the bike is set up fixed.   The upgrades significantly help with the usability and comfort of the bike. The carbon fiber riser bars ‚Äì coupled with the tires -- help to soak up the vibrations that are common with skinny tire steel-bar track bikes. Additionally, the mountain bike bars have been chopped to narrow the overall silhouette of the bike. The overall running position is now much more comfortable yet still sporty. The Paul Components brake lever helps maintain the clean lines of the cockpit while still offering the safety of a brake!  Modifications are as follows: ‚Ä¢	Paul Components Silver E-lever (MSRP $75) https://www.paulcomp.com/shop/components/brake-levers/short-pull/e-lever/ ‚Ä¢	SRAM cranksets (MSRP $100) ‚Ä¢	60 mm Thompson billet aluminum stem (MSPR $40)  ‚Ä¢	40 mm Easton EC70 XC Carbon Riser Bar (MSRP $139) https://www.mountainflyermagazine.com/view.php/tested-easton-ec70-xc-low-rise-handlebar.html ‚Ä¢	BLAQ Freestyle straps (MSRP $58 ) https://blaqpaks.com/accessories/platform-straps ‚Ä¢	WTB Thickslick tires (MSRP $35 x 2) https://www.mountainflyermagazine.com/view.php/tested-easton-ec70-xc-low-rise-handlebar.html  Please email me if you have any questions!

title: 5 mopeds various conditions includes rare Pryor trike
text: Pryor Trike Moped with Moto Minarelli engine. Excellent condition. Ran strong when last used about 5 yrs ago. Will need new plugs, gas and possibly a carb cleaning. -Sachs 5 star General. top tank. Unknown condition, needs a kickstand but otherwise appears complete. Super cool looking bike. -Sachs Hercules. Kind of rough shape w dangling wires and flat tires. Appears mostly complete but definitely missing a few pieces. -Pacer Moped. Two seater (two riders on a moped is illegal in Ohio) unknown condition but mostly complete. -Vespa Piaggio Grande. Incomplete. Has frame, front fork/tire, peddles...see pics. -throwing in all of my extra moped parts and pieces. Lots of upgrade stuff. Foot pegs, mirrors, headlight screens, various handle bars and seats, new chain, green light magnets, a fork lock a speedometer and a high performance Homoet muffler, mud flaps, wind shield and more.  The rarity of the Pryor Trike makes this a super unique lot. Youre unlikely to find another for sale...anywhere. They were made in Ohio and won awards for their patended differential. This bike has custom wood floorboards and trunk. The trike was never quite the fastest moped in my collection but it is the funniest to ride and super reliable. It also easily hauls a cooler! The Sachs 5 Star General Top Tank is one of the most sought after bikes by moped enthusiasts. With a bit of wrenching, this will be well worth my entire lot's asking price on it's own. Dont believe me? Do a quick price check on these mopeds. Feel free to ask any questions, I'm not a mechanic but I'll try to answer and I'll be as honest as possible w my limited knowledge. Gas prices are way up but mopeds are extremely fuel efficient. Pick up at my warehouse garage downtown Cleveland. Delivery available if near Cleveland and w/ payment in advance.

These are the modifications I have done to the bike: Fly Racing aluminum handlebars Progrip 714 Grips Shorty Levers Moose Racing Handguards LED auxiliary lights with handlebar switch LED Headlight, tail light, and turn signals LED turn signal flasher and indicator light diode Supermoto Front Fender Acerbis 5.3 gallon fuel tank Ricochet Skid Plate Procycle Case Savers Procycle Lowered Pegs Procycle Rear Frame guards JNS Rear Master Cylinder Guard Seat Concepts seat (wider, softer) DG exhaust K&N air filter, enlarged airbox holes Rejetted carb, drilled the slide for better throttle response 16t front sprocket for lower highway RPM Tail tidy kit (dr200 tail light, fender delete) Rear Luggage Rack NSU bolts replaced with socket head bolts, crossdrilled and safety wired. 10W fork oil and shock oil for better controlled damping. I am open to offers, but please remember that this bike is 2 1/2 years old with roughly $3000 in aftermarket parts.

title: 2000 Vianelli Corsa
text: Posted this late last year but winter was almost here. Riding weather is back so one last time...  This is a 2000 Vianelli Corsa in excellent condition and ready to ride. It used to be my go-to but I no longer ride like I did.  Tires, cables and housings, chain, brake pads, bar tape were replaced recently. Bike has been refurbished and tuned, all bearings replaced, cleaned and lubricated. Components include the 9x2 speed Campagnolo Daytona group (18 speeds total), Campagnolo Athena headset and cartridge bottom bracket, Miche seatpost, Shimano SPD-S pedals, Velocity Fusion rimmed wheels with Campagnolo hubs and Vittoria Rubino 23c tires.  Size is 62cm (24.4 inches) center crank to top of seat tube. Stand-over clearance at the top tube is 33.5 inches and the bike will fit from 32 - 36 inch inseams with some variation depending on the individual.  Top tube is 58cm center-center.   The frame is constructed of Dedaccaiai Zero Uno, very light and strong Italian butted steel tubing with Columbus dropouts.  The bike weighs just under 23lbs as pictured.  The craftsmanship is very good - The joins, chrome and paintwork are excellent.   $500 cash and local pick up only please. Text and emails are preferred between 9am and 6pm.  Some background on the brand:  Vianelli bikes are more common in Italy than here in the US, they were not widely exported. Made in Brescia where Pierfranco Vianelli opened his shop after retiring from professional cycling. This bike was purchased from the original owner in Brescia.  Vianelli won the 1968 Olympics gold medal in the Individual Road Race, after he left racing he built bikes himself and also built frames for Marinoni. Later he also contracted some out to area framebuilders.  Vianelli still has a store in Brescia, now run by his son.

title: Kona Hei Hei
text: A very clean Kona Hei Hei Full suspension mountain bike. If you got this far you likely know what your looking at. One of the lightest full suspension mountain bikes on the planet. This one has been babied and is fully tuned,serviced and ready to go. No issues. Does not include pedals or water bottle holder. You would be very hard pressed to find one of these anywhere near this condition for this price. Frame is scandium. Lighter than aluminum and stronger than carbon fiber.

title: Juiced Bikes Scorpion
text: Selling my Scorpion as I don't use it much. Been in storage for a while collecting dust, has less than 300 miles(will verify). Comes with the original charger too.   Also has the bike horn to alert others and extremely bright headlight/taillights. I've fallen once on it and the left handle bar tip has Some scratches from gliding on cement(Check Pictures). Overall works well and was super fun to use I just don't use it anymore and want to get rid of it.   Speed is 18-22mph, you can do 28mph if you add the off- road mod from their website.   Range is up to 75miles and parts for this are easily found on the manufacturer website apart from very thorough manuals for disassembly or repair.   Paid $2500 for it. Priced to sell or Best Offer.

title: unisky Bike Trainer
text: Selling used unisky Bike Trainer, as I am upgrading to a stationary bike for my home gym.  Listing details:  * QUICK RELEASE: The handle at the stationary bike trainer not only can release the bike off the trainer quickly by lifting up, but also can lock the bike to the trainer quickly by pressing down. Very simple and convenient, the indoor bike trainer is easy for everyone to handle. * 6 SPEED RESISTANCE: With a remote controller of 6-level speed by a wire, you can change resistance to comply with the cycling conditions you want and enjoy different riding experiences. After quick installation, you can begin to ride. 1-2 speed offer less resistance when comparing with the 5 or 6 spped. * STEADY, STABLE AND FIRM: The indoor exercise bike trainer is designed with dual-support structure. The wide frame and front wheel riser block included in the package keep it away from wobbling and reach unshakable balance. The steady base and adjustable anti-slip rubber feet fits for uneven floor in different conditions, preventing movement for stability on any surface. * SMOOTH IN SPIN: When riding a bike at home, a smooth bike exercise trainer is definitely necessary. Bike trainer with noise reduction resistance wheel makes your cycling virtually silent. BTW, if noise is loud, it has a lot to do with the materials and tread of bike tires, we sincerely suggest you to use a slick tire. * COMPATIBLE WITH BIKES: The Unisky indoor riding bicycle training stand fits bikes with a 26-28" or 700c wheel, most road or mountain bikes . There is no need to buy a new one if you have a road or mountain bike of normal size. Bring your bike inside and begin indoor cycling workout. After exercise, take the bike off the trainer, fold the bike trainer and put it at any corner.  Load capacity 300lb

title: Heavy duty Yakima HoldUp 4 Bike Rack Platform Style Tilting 2" Hitches
text: Due to so much scam calls and emails recently asking for address, please do not call nor email, but only text me to  show contact info  Yakima HoldUp 4 Bike Rack - Platform Style - Tilting - 2" Hitches Tilting Design and Compact Storage The HoldUp has a spring-loaded pin at the base that lets you fold the rack up against the rear of your vehicle when it's not in use. The same pin can also be used to tilt the rack down 20 degrees for easier bike loading. The tilting feature can also be used when the is rack fully loaded, so you can gain easier access to your vehicle's rear cargo area without unloading your bikes.  Removable 2-Bike Add-On The rack includes a 2-bike add-on that installs easily onto the base rack. When it's not needed, simply remove the add-on with the included special tool and throw it in your trunk or leave it at home. To install the add-on on your HoldUp, simply remove the endcap from the bike rack base, slide the add-on's shank into the hole on the bike rack, and secure the shank with a bolt that comes with the add-on. The add-on includes a safty flag post to ensure that the rack is visible to other vehicles on the road.   Wheel-Mount Design for Easy Bike Loading The HoldUp is easy to load, even if your bikes have monster wheels. The deep, contoured front wheel cradles accommodate just about any wheel out there, and the pivoting arms with StrongArm technology ensure that your bikes are held firmly in place. To load a bike, simply place your front wheel in the holder, rotate the pivoting arm up and over the wheel, and press down firmly on the ratcheting hook. To release the hook, simply press the built-in red button and slide the hook up and off your wheel. Large rear wheel holders allow the HoldUp to accommodate a wide variety of bike wheelbases. These wheel holders pivot front to back, adjusting automatically to your wheel size - no need for sliding and tightening. Secure the wheels in place with the ratcheting straps built into each holder. Mounting bikes by the wheels helps prevent any scratches or scuffs to the paint. The ratcheting hooks are padded, however, so they won't mar your wheels. And the pivot mechanisms in the arms are overbuilt to ensure they keep functioning smoothly over a lifetime of hard use.

title: VINTAGE FREE SPIRIT  MAN'S BIKE
text: Rare vintage ('60's or '70's) survivor.  Not many men's bikes survived.     Free Spirit was a Sears and Roebuck brand.  Their name does not appear on the bike. "Sunbird" does appear on the crossbar.  I assume it is a model name.    It is a 10 speed with two levers as shown in photos.  Both cables are attached to front and rear derailleurs.  They work but need adjusting. Hand brakes are cable operated but need adjusting.    Wheels are 27" and use 27 x 1 1/4 tires and tubes.  Both wheels are true.  Tires appear to be original to the bike.  They are will need replacing.   Should be perfect for restoration without a lot of time and expensive parts.  Everything is there.   All cables and the chain are in good shape.  Nothing on the bike is frozen up and is still usable.    The maroon paint looks great even for its age.  The chrome handlebars have some surface rust but will clean up just fine with some naval jelly and steel wool. One photo attempts to show my quick effort to show this.     Frame size is probably a Large.  Around 6 feet and taller will be comfortable.

title: $3200 Trek Domane / 4.7 / full carbon / full Ultegra
text: Super clean, low-mileage Trek Domane 4.7 for sale.  $3200 new.  Full carbon frameset.  Full Ultegra groupset.  This model has Trek's ISOSpeed feature... for an even smoother ride than carbon fiber frames already give.  https://www.trekbikes.com/us/en_US/inside_trek/isospeed/  Frame sticker says this is a 56cm.  But also says the top tube is more of a 55cm.  Complete specs here:  https://archive.trekbikes.com/ca/en/2014/Trek/domane_4_7_wsd_compact  Technically this is a WSD / women's model... but road bike frames are unisex so only the "touch points" are different (handlebar and saddle) on the female versions... and the paint colors / graphics.  And this particular color scheme is not particularly girly.  (White and charcoal w/ a couple of dark fuscia TREK logos.)  In terms of sizing, if you ride a 56cm bike, you ride a 56cm bike... there is no "womens 56cm" or "mens 56cm".  56cm is 56cm.   Bike has normal wear from typical recreational riding... but overall is in fantastic condition.  Height-wise, for a 55/56cm frame you should be in the 5'8 to 5'11 range... but could certainly work for someone a little smaller or a little taller with some fitting.  I will include the after-market accessories... water bottle cages, tail bag (behind the saddle), and frame bag (behind stem)... and the CatEye trip computer.    The bike was just at Fletcher Bike Studio in Montrose getting new bar tape and a light tune up / adjustment... just to make sure it is perfect for the next owner.  (Great bike shop by the way!)  The Domane is Trek's "endurance" road platform... which means less aggressive / more comfortable right out of the box than their racier bikes (like the Madone and the Emonda).  You could certainly tweak this bike to get it more racey if that's what you're looking for.  But most people are looking for a good combination of speed and comfort.  And that's what the Domane is all about.  Love the bike but I upgraded to a newer model.  54cm 55cm 57cm specialzed roubaix giant propel tcr defy 54 55 56 cm

title: Trek Madone 5.2 / $3k new [58cm] full carbon w full Ultegra
text: Super clean Trek Madone 5.2 full carbon road bike for sale.  $3000+ new  Color is kind of a charcoal nude pearl carbon... with just a grey-ish tint to the clear coat over the carbon fiber material.  Looks tight.  58cm full OCLV carbon fiber frameset. (Ideal for riders in the 5'-10" to 6'-2" range... with the sweet spot being somewhere in the middle.)   Full Shimano Ultegra groupset.   (3x10 w/ a (rare) long cage rear derailleur for larger cassette capacity) = 30 speeds.  Excellent for weekend hill country riding, MS-150, the Rockies on vacation, etc.  The bike is in very good condition, with normal wear from typical riding. Never crashed. Always stored indoors and professionally maintained.   Just had Fletcher Bike Studio install a brand new ($65 Ultegra 12/23) cassette and brand new ($35 KMC) chain + new cables and housings, then re-adjust shifting to perfection.  Also had them re-wrap the bars with new bar tape.  (Total = $150)  So, short of a major component or wheel failure--which is rare--the bike should be good for thousands of miles without needing any major service.  This bike is very light for a road bike (around 17 to 17.5 lbs).  The 5.2 Madones are very highly rated / reviewed by their owners.  https://www.roadbikereview.com/product/latest-bikes/road-bike/trek/madone-5-2.html?p=8  This particular bike is more or less factory original... with the exception of upgraded wheels and tires (red anodized Mavic Heliums with red Continental Grand Prix 4000's) and the water bottle cages... and the above mentioned major service that was just done.  (Zero miles since service.)  Bike is 100% ready for the road today.  Needs nothing at all.  Just clip in and go.  Reply with any questions not covered here or to set up a time to check out the bike in person.  57cm 59cm 57 cm 58 cm 59 cm emonda domane pilot giant advanced specialized tarmac specialized roubaix giant defy ocr tcr

title: Rebuilt CB 750
text: This classic CB750K SOHC has been an amazing bike for me. 	‚ÅÉ	The carbs have been cleaned, tuned, and synced on a number of occasions. 	‚ÅÉ	The motor was ‚Äúrebuilt‚Äù 2 years ago. The rebuild included several modifications that are debatably factory due to the fact that I hunted and picked through the bone yard to pull the very best K0 camshaft, cam towers, rockers, shafts, etc. I pieced each together utilizing the best of each year of the 750 to maximize the power output ‚ÄúWITHOUT‚Äù increasing displacement. Essentially this bike has been gone through with power in mind, but I have not bored it out. Rather old parts have been replaced with either new stock sizes or lightly used parts. Everything and I mean EVERYTHING in the top end has been hand lightened, the head completely ported and polished, including combustion chambers, as well as domed (higher compression) pistons installed.  	‚ÅÉ	All electrical parts have been gone through with the points replaced, then essentially bypassed with a transistorized ignition, new coils, upgraded advance unit, modified advance springs, and so on. All in all everything is LED and the headlight alone is amazing to say the least. The electrical upgrades completely removed the 750 flat spot in the mid range and have overall reduced the workload that the wiring has to deal with. All of this improves reliability, performance, and safety.  	‚ÅÉ	The tires alone are over $500 in rubber and MAN do they hug the corners. 	‚ÅÉ	The suspension has been completely gone through, with fork seals and oil replaced. The triple tree clamps cracked on me on my way to work one day, so I bought a joker machine replacement set that are solid billet aluminum with taper steering stem bearings installed. 	‚ÅÉ	The front and rear wheels have been professionally trued and bearing have been replaced with the tires at end of last riding season.  	‚ÅÉ	The front wheels hub does not come stock setup to be able to receive a second (yes that‚Äôs right second, as in dual disk) disk, but I have machined the hub and have the second disk on the front wheel now. I also have the second brake setup complete, but you would just need to get the brake line for it. Cool part about the triple clamp is that it actually acts as the hydraulic splitter for the front end. So everything is set to go, I just never got around to getting it done.  	‚ÅÉ	There are two completely different set of pipes based on your preference. One is an after market 4 into 1 that is on it now. I personally don‚Äôt like or prefer this set, but haven‚Äôt had the time to swap them back to the original 4 into 4 chrome pipes. With all of the upgrades done to bike I thought it might do well with the 4 into 1 pipe, but honestly have been disappointed. The performance, sound, and look of the originals far out way the 4 into 1 set. Both come with the bike though.   I could go on and on about this bike if you couldn‚Äôt tell, but sadly a ‚Äúdeal with the devil‚Äù, just kidding a deal with my wife is causing me to have to give this prize up. Lame or stupid as I may sound I REALLY REALLY want this bike to go to someone who will love it the way that I have. Give it a good home if you will. The trick with ‚Äúold‚Äù bikes is that they need a certain amount of care and most people don‚Äôt get that. They just ride it and don‚Äôt take care of what they have. Really the only thing that hasn‚Äôt been updated in this bike is it‚Äôs cosmetics. The tank has a small ding and a scratch, but the seat, tank, and side panels are all from the 70‚Äôs. Quality stuff really.  I also have two full bins chalk full of parts for this baby. I am happy to include most of them.

title: 1980 Yamaha Towny Electric Moped
text: This is my 1980 Yamaha Towny which I converted to electric. It has a 60 volt, 1800 watt electrical system.  The batteries are each 16s2p (60 volt, 6 amp-hours) batteries, which are connected in parallel for greater capacity (60 volt, 12 amp-hours). I know the label on the batteries says they are 20000 mAh, but that's not true - just a fake value from the distributor.  The motor is a 48v, 1500w hub motor, which I have over-volted to 60v for greater top speed.  The top speed of the bike is about 25 mph, and the range is about 10 miles. Not a ton of range, but good for quick trips around town.  Feel free to reach out with any questions! I accept cash and Venmo - no trades. Text only, and I'm open to offers.  Thanks!

title: 1980 Honda CR 900 Motorcycle   - VALUE PRICED TO SELL!
text: 1980 Honda CR 900 Motorcycle   - VALUE PRICED TO SELL!32,923 mi. - Manual - Standard -  - VIN# SC042003172 - STK# 003172Desert Private Collection Call or Text (760) 313-6607https://www.desertprivatecollection.com Address: 39625 Entrepreneur Ln, Palm Desert, CA 92211Honda CB900CClaimed power: 83hp @ 8,500rpmTop speed: 132mphEngine: 902cc air-cooled DOHC 16-valve inline fourWeight: 588lb (wet)Price then/now: $3,349 (1980)/$1,500-$2,500¬† The term Factory Custom may be an oxymoron, but the 1980 Honda CB900C was Honda‚Äôs early attempt at blending sporting performance with cruiser credibility and touring capability. Did it succeed? Or was it just trying to please all the people all the time? Around 1980, the full-size motorcycle market began splintering into numerous niches, including the Factory Custom. Seats grew steps, bars pulled back, footpegs inched forward, and clean drive shafts replaced messy chains. No doubt mindful that its game-changing V4s were in the pipeline, Honda stretched its trusty 4-valve inline 750cc to 900cc, then laid back its ergonomics to take on Suzuki‚Äôs cruiser GS850/1100GL and Yamaha‚Äôs similarly-themed XS1100 Special. Essentially, Honda hijacked the engine from its Euro-spec CB900F to power the CB900C. The air-cooled, 16-valve double overhead cam with pent-roof combustion chambers was fed by four 32mm Keihin carburetors. A single-piece forged crankshaft drove a jackshaft via a Hy-Vo chain, with gear drive from the jackshaft to the clutch and 5-speed tranny. Shaft drive was de rigueur in the custom class, so to keep development costs down Honda borrowed the final drive unit from the GL1100 to use on the 900C. There was, however, one minor problem using the GL unit: the CB900‚Äôs tranny output was on the bike‚Äôs left side, and the GL1100‚Äôs shaft was on the right. Honda‚Äôs solution was a crossover shaft ‚Äî actually, two shafts incorporating two pairs of gears. This gave the CB900C a 2-speed ‚ÄúSelect Range‚Äù secondary transmission sitting in its own transfer case, complete with its own trochoidal oil pump for lubrication. And while it wasn‚Äôt as complicated as it sounds, it wasn‚Äôt exactly simple.¬†Cycle¬†magazine counted ‚Äú20 gears, six shafts, a dozen bearings, three torque cushions, a U-joint and assorted couplings employed in making the crank/rear wheel connection.‚Äù The 2-speed transfer case meant 10 forward gears, giving CB900C riders incredible flexibility in gearing. It also went a long way toward the bike‚Äôs reasonable fuel economy. Kept in ‚Äúhigh‚Äù range, reports of 50mpg were common. That said, left in ‚Äúlow‚Äù range and ridden with a heavy right hand the CB900C would return as little as 30mpg. Yet the multitude of driveline components allowed generous driveline lash, which, combined with lean EPA-mandated carburetion, made for herky-jerky throttle transitions ‚Äúthe like of which you won‚Äôt find in any other motorcycle presently in production,‚Äù¬†Cycle¬†said. The extra transmission case also stretched the frame, and thus lengthened the wheelbase to a Harley-esque 62 inches ‚Äî even using a short swingarm. This latter item introduced its own problems, causing noticeable torque jacking under acceleration and a lack of rear end traction under braking, chirping the rear tire. And the C-bike weighed in at nearly 590 pounds ready to ride, making it just about the heaviest machine in its class. In most other respects, though, the 900C worked really well. Testers praised its electric-motor-like power delivery; lack of vibration (the engine was rubber-mounted); straight-line performance (less than 12.5 seconds at almost 110mph in the quarter mile ‚Äî on¬† par with the XS11 and GS11); adjustable air-assisted suspension (also derived from the GL1100); and even its handling ‚Äî in spite of a lazy 29-degree steering angle and squirmy 16-inch rear tire. Comfort was good (though the stepped seat trapped the rider in one position), brakes powerful and resistant to fade, and the 2-speed tranny reduced engine speed by a useful 500rpm at highway cruising speeds ‚Äî and fuel consumption by as much as 16 percent if left in high. Even so,¬†Cycle Guide¬†concluded the extra five gears ‚Äúbordered on the redundant‚Äù and a similar result ‚Äúcould easily have been accomplished with a 6-speed transmission.‚Äù Built to Honda‚Äôs typically high standards, CB900Cs could pile on the miles. The 2-speed transfer case doesn‚Äôt appear to have any negative impact on reliability, and like other Honda fours the 900C had few major problem areas. But what really baffled testers was how to classify the CB900C. Was it a cruiser, a tourer or a new type of sport bike? Though intended to appeal to American buyers, the custom styling left¬†Cycle Guide¬†testers cold. One called it the ‚ÄúKing Kong Kompromise Kruiser,‚Äù while another considered it a dinosaur and hoped its inevitable extinction would ‚Äúmark a return to a more sensible line of motorcycles where sheer size is not a prime factor.‚Äù A third thought it had been ‚Äúdressed by committee.‚Äù Ultimately, it was a bike in search of a market, and while briefly popular, it was dropped after just three years in Honda‚Äôs lineup. It‚Äôs perhaps ironic to note that the CB900C, a decidedly large bike when introduced, looks like a featherweight alongside today‚Äôs gargantuan boulevard bikes. Maybe it was just 30 years ahead of its time.WE BUY CARS AND CONSIGN CARSMORE PICTURES and VIDEO CLIPS ON OUR WEBSITE: www.DesertPrivateCollection.comWE BUY CLASSIC CARS - CONSIGN and SELL -¬†PHOTO SHOOT RENTAL IS AVAILABLECalifornia buyers must pay CA sales tax , all prices in USD .¬† Disclaimer-Finance Requirements listed at our website-Price does not include sales tax and DMV registration feesMonthly payment is based on approved Credit for more Inventory VISIT OUR WEBSITE¬†https://www.desertprivatecollection.com/ or call¬†(760) 313-6607FOR CONSIGNMENT PLEASE CONTACT¬†US¬†(760) 313-6607This head turning 1980 Honda CR 900 Standard fits your budget at $2,750.
